🔐 1️⃣ What is SAML Authentication? (From Scratch)
✅ SAML = Security Assertion Markup Language
It is an XML-based authentication protocol used for Single Sign-On (SSO).
It allows:


One system → authenticate user


Another system → trust that authentication



🏢 Real World Example (Your Rails App + ADFS)
In your project:


Your Rails App = Service Provider (SP)


ADFS = Identity Provider (IdP)


Flow:


User visits Rails app


Rails redirects user to ADFS


User logs in with company credentials


ADFS sends back a signed SAML response (XML)


Rails verifies it


User is logged in



🔁 SAML Authentication Flow (Line-by-Line)
Let’s break it like you’ll explain in interview.

Step 1: User tries to access protected route
before_action :authenticate_user!

If not logged in → redirect to SAML provider.

Step 2: Rails sends SAML Request to ADFS
Using OmniAuth SAML:
Rails.application.config.middleware.use OmniAuth::Builder do
  provider :saml,
           idp_sso_target_url: "https://adfs.company.com/adfs/ls/",
           idp_cert: "ADFS_CERTIFICATE",
           issuer: "https://yourapp.com"
end

Rails generates a SAML AuthnRequest (XML).

Step 3: ADFS authenticates user
User enters:


Domain username


Password


MFA (maybe)



Step 4: ADFS sends back SAML Response (XML)
Example simplified SAML Response:
<samlp:Response>
  <saml:Assertion>
    <saml:Subject>
      <saml:NameID>shubham@company.com</saml:NameID>
    </saml:Subject>

    <saml:AttributeStatement>
      <saml:Attribute Name="email">
        <saml:AttributeValue>shubham@company.com</saml:AttributeValue>
      </saml:Attribute>

      <saml:Attribute Name="role">
        <saml:AttributeValue>admin</saml:AttributeValue>
      </saml:Attribute>
    </saml:AttributeStatement>
  </saml:Assertion>
</samlp:Response>

This is:
👉 XML
👉 Digitally signed
👉 Contains user identity

Step 5: Rails verifies SAML Response
Rails verifies:


✅ XML Signature


✅ Certificate


✅ Issuer


✅ Expiry time


✅ Audience


If valid → user is authenticated.

